Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

I'm not convinced we really want to rely on this lib.

The last release in pypi is from April 2013 (which itself wouldn't really be a problem) but the project page directs to code.google.com and unless moved the source repos will not be available after January 2016.

Carrying our own implementation of such a simple class seems quite low overhead & risk compared to moving to dead project.
Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

Patch Set 3: Code-Review-2

We should drive towards removing this from global requirements as it's not maintained, rather than widen it's use.

Patch Set 3:

It'd be better to have a plan to adopt it since we use it everywhere. We already did that several times with Oslo.

Patch Set 3:

That would be perfectly fine by me, lets adobt it and revisit this when the lib is under maintenance. The change looks fine by me, I just really really don't want to consume something which state will be dead at January.

Patch Set 3:

I don't think spending time to start maintaining something that do not seems to have any bug right now nor we had problem with is a good spend of our time.

Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

@Erno,

While I understand where you're coming from (and I totally agree with you), I think we could make an "exception" in this case. Here are some points to explain my reasoning:

1. We already use PrettyTable in glanceclient. This doesn't mean we should use it here too but it does mean we need to either move this, self-maintained, implementation to glanceclient (which we moved away from a couple of cycles ago IIRC) or we (OpenStack) need to adopt PrettyTable and help maintaining it.

2. Many projects are using it already, which means it'll likely be adopted by the community OR replaced.

3. Along #2, in the case where the library is not adopted but replaced, I think we would benefit from having consistency accross projects and make migrations simpler to whatever we choose (if we decide to move away from PrettyTable).

I'm personally not worried about adopting it because the version we depend on is stable enough, it's capped, and it won't be removed from pypi.

How strongly do you feel about not accepting this change? Any way we can persuade you? Does the above make sense (At least a bit)?

I'm +2ing based on the condition that I know we won't be left abandoned with a non-working library in case it goes away as we're not the only ones currently using it.

Patch Set 3:

Can someone +A so we can move on now?

Patch Set 3:

I can approve, but at first you have to convince Erno to remove -2

Patch Set 3:

I'm still strongly opposed to consuming code that is going to EOL in months time.

That said we're working with Flavio towards solution for this.
